  "prompt": "Can I use open source software for commercial use? how ?",
  "response": "Yes, you can use open source software for commercial use, but there are some important considerations:\n\n1. Check the License\nDifferent open source licenses have different terms:\n\nA. Permissive Licenses (Most Business-Friendly)\n- MIT License\n- Apache License\n- BSD License\n- Allow commercial use\n- Minimal restrictions\n\nB. Copyleft Licenses (More Restrictive)\n- GNU General Public License (GPL)\n- Require sharing source code if you modify the software\n- May limit commercial use\n\n2. Common Commercial Use Scenarios\n\nA. Using as-is\n- Install and use open source software without modification\n- Most licenses allow this\n\nB. Modifying software\n- Check specific license terms\n- Some require publishing modifications\n- Some require attribution\n\n3. Best Practices\n\n- Carefully read the specific license\n- Consult legal counsel\n- Maintain proper attribution\n- Comply with license terms\n- Track license compliance\n\n4. Examples of Commercial Open Source Use\n- Linux servers\n- WordPress\n- Android\n- PostgreSQL\n- Redis\n\n5. Recommended Steps\n- Verify license\n- Document usage\n- Keep original license intact\n- Provide attribution if required\n\nAlways consult legal professionals for specific guidance.",
